# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chi-squared-tests
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] In probability theory and statistics, the **$\chi ^{2}$ -distribution** with k degrees of freedom is the distribution of a sum of the squares of k independent standard normal random variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution $\chi _{k}^{2}$ is a special case of the gamma distribution and the univariate Wishart distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Specifically if $X\sim \chi _{k}^{2}$ then ${\textstyle X\sim {\text{Gamma}}(\alpha ={\frac {k}{2}},\theta =2)}$ (where $\alpha$ is the shape parameter and $\theta$ the scale parameter of the gamma distribution) and $X\sim {\text{W}}_{1}(1,k)$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The **scaled chi-squared distribution** $s^{2}\chi _{k}^{2}$ is a reparametrization of the gamma distribution and the univariate Wishart distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is one of the most widely used probability distributions in inferential statistics, notably in hypothesis testing and in construction of confidence intervals.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] This distribution is sometimes called the **central chi-squared distribution**, a special case of the more general noncentral chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Many other statistical tests also use this distribution, such as Friedman's analysis of variance by ranks.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] If *Z*1, ..., *Z**k* are independent, standard normal random variables, then the sum of their squares, $X\ =\sum _{i=1}^{k}Z_{i}^{2},$ is distributed according to the chi-squared distribution with k degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution has one parameter: a positive integer k that specifies the number of degrees of freedom (the number of random variables *Z**i* being summed).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is used primarily in hypothesis testing, and to a lesser extent for confidence intervals for population variance when the underlying distribution is normal.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Unlike more widely known distributions such as the normal distribution and the exponential distribution, the chi-squared distribution is not as often applied in the direct modeling of natural phenomena.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] It is also a component of the definition of the *t*-distribution and the *F*-distribution used in *t*-tests, analysis of variance, and regression analysis.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The primary reason for which the chi-squared distribution is extensively used in hypothesis testing is its relationship to the normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Many hypothesis tests use a test statistic, such as the *t*-statistic in a *t*-test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For these hypothesis tests, as the sample size, n, increases, the sampling distribution of the test statistic approaches the normal distribution (central limit theorem).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Because the test statistic (such as t) is asymptotically normally distributed, provided the sample size is sufficiently large, the distribution used for hypothesis testing may be approximated by a normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Testing hypotheses using a normal distribution is well understood and relatively easy.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The simplest chi-squared distribution is the square of a standard normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] So wherever a normal distribution could be used for a hypothesis test, a chi-squared distribution could be used.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Suppose that Z is a random variable sampled from the standard normal distribution, where the mean is 0 and the variance is 1 : $Z\sim N(0,1)$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Now, consider the random variable $X=Z^{2}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The distribution of the random variable X is an example of a chi-squared distribution: $\ X\ \sim \ \chi _{1}^{2}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The subscript 1 indicates that this particular chi-squared distribution is constructed from only 1 standard normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] A chi-squared distribution constructed by squaring a single standard normal distribution is said to have 1 degree of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Thus, as the sample size for a hypothesis test increases, the distribution of the test statistic approaches a normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Just as extreme values of the normal distribution have low probability (and give small p-values), extreme values of the chi-squared distribution have low probability.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] An additional reason that the chi-squared distribution is widely used is that it turns up as the large sample distribution of generalized likelihood ratio tests (LRT).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] LRTs have several desirable properties; in particular, simple LRTs commonly provide the highest power to reject the null hypothesis (Neyman–Pearson lemma) and this leads also to optimality properties of generalised LRTs.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] However, the normal and chi-squared approximations are only valid asymptotically.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For this reason, it is preferable to use the *t* distribution rather than the normal approximation or the chi-squared approximation for a small sample size.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Similarly, in analyses of contingency tables, the chi-squared approximation will be poor for a small sample size, and it is preferable to use Fisher's exact test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Ramsey shows that the exact binomial test is always more powerful than the normal approximation.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Lancaster shows the connections among the binomial, normal, and chi-squared distributions, as follows.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] De Moivre and Laplace established that a binomial distribution could be approximated by a normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] where m is the observed number of successes in N trials, where the probability of success is p , and $q=1-p$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] In the case of a binomial outcome (flipping a coin), the binomial distribution may be approximated by a normal distribution (for sufficiently large n ).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] However, many problems involve more than the two possible outcomes of a binomial, and instead require 3 or more categories, which leads to the multinomial distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Just as de Moivre and Laplace sought for and found the normal approximation to the binomial, Pearson sought for and found a degenerate multivariate normal approximation to the multinomial distribution (the numbers in each category add up to the total sample size, which is considered fixed).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Pearson showed that the chi-squared distribution arose from such a multivariate normal approximation to the multinomial distribution, taking careful account of the statistical dependence (negative correlations) between numbers of observations in different categories.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For derivations of the pdf in the cases of one, two and k degrees of freedom, see Proofs related to chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] In a special case of $k=2$ this function has the simple form: $F(x;\,2)=1-e^{-x/2}$ which can be easily derived by integrating ${\textstyle f(x;\,2)={\frac {1}{2}}e^{-x/2}}$ directly.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The integer recurrence of the gamma function makes it easy to compute $F(x;\,k)$ for other small, even k .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Tables of the chi-squared cumulative distribution function are widely available and the function is included in many spreadsheets and all statistical packages.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Letting $z\equiv x/k$ , Chernoff bounds on the lower and upper tails of the CDF may be obtained.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For another approximation for the CDF modeled after the cube of a Gaussian, see under Noncentral chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The following is a special case of Cochran's theorem.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] It follows from the definition of the chi-squared distribution that the sum of independent chi-squared variables is also chi-squared distributed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Specifically, if $X_{i},i={\overline {1,n}}$ are independent chi-squared variables with $k_{i}$ , $i={\overline {1,n}}$ degrees of freedom, respectively, then $Y=X_{1}+\cdots +X_{n}$ is chi-squared distributed with $k_{1}+\cdots +k_{n}$ degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is the maximum entropy probability distribution for a random variate X for which $\operatorname {E} (X)=k$ and $\operatorname {E} (\ln(X))=\psi (k/2)+\ln(2)$ are fixed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Since the chi-squared is in the family of gamma distributions, this can be derived by substituting appropriate values in the Expectation of the log moment of gamma.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For derivation from more basic principles, see the derivation in moment-generating function of the sufficient statistic.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The cumulants are readily obtained by a power series expansion of the logarithm of the characteristic function: $\kappa _{n}=2^{n-1}(n-1)!\,k$ with cumulant generating function ${\textstyle \ln \operatorname {E} [e^{tX}]=-{\frac {k}{2}}\ln(1-2t)}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution exhibits strong concentration around its mean.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] By the central limit theorem, because the chi-squared distribution is the sum of k independent random variables with finite mean and variance, it converges to a normal distribution for large k .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] For many practical purposes, for $k>50$ the distribution is sufficiently close to a normal distribution, so the difference is ignorable.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Specifically, if $X\sim \chi ^{2}(k)$ , then as k tends to infinity, the distribution of $(X-k)/{\sqrt {2k}}$ tends to a standard normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] However, convergence is slow as the skewness is ${\textstyle {\sqrt {8/k}}}$ and the excess kurtosis is $12/k$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The sampling distribution of $\ln(\chi ^{2})$ converges to normality much faster than the sampling distribution of $\chi ^{2}$ , as the logarithmic transform removes much of the asymmetry.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Other functions of the chi-squared distribution converge more rapidly to a normal distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] A chi-squared variable with k degrees of freedom is defined as the sum of the squares of k independent standard normal random variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] If Y is a k -dimensional Gaussian random vector with mean vector $\mu$ and rank k covariance matrix C , then $X=(Y-\mu )^{\mathsf {T}}C^{-1}(Y-\mu )$ is chi-squared distributed with k degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The sum of squares of statistically independent unit-variance Gaussian variables which do *not* have mean zero yields a generalization of the chi-squared distribution called the noncentral chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] If Y is a vector of k i.i.d. standard normal random variables and A is a $k\times k$ symmetric, idempotent matrix with rank $k-n$ , then the quadratic form $Y^{\mathsf {T}}\!AY$ is chi-square distributed with $k-n$ degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is also naturally related to other distributions arising from the Gaussian.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is obtained as the sum of the squares of k independent, zero-mean, unit-variance Gaussian random variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Generalizations of this distribution can be obtained by summing the squares of other types of Gaussian random variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Several such distributions are described below.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] If $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are chi square random variables and $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}\in \mathbb {R} _{>0}$ , then the distribution of ${\textstyle X=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{i}}$ is a special case of the generalized chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] A closed expression for this distribution is not known.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] It may be, however, approximated efficiently using the property of characteristic functions of chi-square random variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The noncentral chi-squared distribution is obtained from the sum of the squares of independent Gaussian random variables having unit variance and *nonzero* means.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The generalized chi-squared distribution is obtained from the quadratic form z'Az where z is a zero-mean Gaussian vector having an arbitrary covariance matrix, and A is an arbitrary matrix.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Because the exponential distribution is also a special case of the gamma distribution, we also have that if $X\sim \chi _{2}^{2}$ , then ${\textstyle X\sim \operatorname {exp} \left({\tfrac {1}{2}}\right)}$ is an exponential distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The Erlang distribution is also a special case of the gamma distribution and thus we also have that if $X\sim \chi _{k}^{2}$ with even k , then X is Erlang distributed with shape parameter $k/2$ and scale parameter $1/2$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution has numerous applications in inferential statistics, for instance in chi-squared tests and in estimating variances.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] It enters the problem of estimating the mean of a normally distributed population and the problem of estimating the slope of a regression line via its role in Student's t-distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] It enters all analysis of variance problems via its role in the F-distribution, which is the distribution of the ratio of two independent chi-squared random variables, each divided by their respective degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Following are some of the most common situations in which the chi-squared distribution arises from a Gaussian-distributed sample.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is also often encountered in magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The ${\textstyle p}$ -value is the probability of observing a test statistic *at least* as extreme in a chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Accordingly, since the cumulative distribution function (CDF) for the appropriate degrees of freedom *(df)* gives the probability of having obtained a value *less extreme* than this point, subtracting the CDF value from 1 gives the *p*-value.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] A low *p*-value, below the chosen significance level, indicates statistical significance, i.e., sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] A significance level of 0.05 is often used as the cutoff between significant and non-significant results.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The table below gives a number of *p*-values matching to $\chi ^{2}$ for the first 10 degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] These values can be calculated evaluating the quantile function (also known as "inverse CDF" or "ICDF") of the chi-squared distribution; e. g., the χ2 ICDF for *p* = 0.05 and df = 7 yields 2.1673 ≈ 2.17 as in the table above, noticing that 1 – *p* is the *p*-value from the table.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] This distribution was first described by the German geodesist and statistician Friedrich Robert Helmert in papers of 1875–6, where he computed the sampling distribution of the sample variance of a normal population.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] Thus in German this was traditionally known as the *Helmert'sche* ("Helmertian") or "Helmert distribution".
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The name "chi-square" ultimately derives from Pearson's shorthand for the exponent in a multivariate normal distribution with the Greek letter Chi, writing −1⁄2*χ*2 for what would appear in modern notation as −1⁄2**x**TΣ−1**x** (Σ being the covariance matrix).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-distribution] The idea of a family of "chi-squared distributions", however, is not due to Pearson but arose as a further development due to Fisher in the 1920s.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] A **chi-squared test** (also **chi-square** or **χ2 test**) is a statistical hypothesis test used in the analysis of contingency tables when the sample sizes are large.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In simpler terms, this test is primarily used to examine whether two categorical variables (*two dimensions of the contingency table*) are independent in influencing the test statistic (*values within the table*).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The test is valid when the test statistic is chi-squared distributed under the null hypothesis, specifically Pearson's chi-squared test and variants thereof.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Pearson's chi-squared test is used to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference between the expected frequencies and the observed frequencies in one or more categories of a contingency table.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] For contingency tables with smaller sample sizes, a Fisher's exact test is used instead.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In the standard applications of this test, the observations are classified into mutually exclusive classes.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] If the null hypothesis that there are no differences between the classes in the population is true, the test statistic computed from the observations follows a χ2 frequency distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The purpose of the test is to evaluate how likely the observed frequencies would be assuming the null hypothesis is true.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Test statistics that follow a χ2 distribution occur when the observations are independent.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] There are also χ2 tests for testing the null hypothesis of independence of a pair of random variables based on observations of the pairs.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] At the end of the 19th century, Pearson noticed the existence of significant skewness within some biological observations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In 1900, Pearson published a paper on the χ2 test which is considered to be one of the foundations of modern statistics.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In this paper, Pearson investigated a test of goodness of fit.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Suppose that n observations in a random sample from a population are classified into k mutually exclusive classes with respective observed numbers of observations xi (for *i* = 1,2,…,*k*), and a null hypothesis gives the probability pi that an observation falls into the ith class.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Pearson proposed that, under the circumstance of the null hypothesis being correct, as *n* → ∞ the limiting distribution of the quantity given below is the χ2 distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] will usually be positive and small enough to be omitted.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In a conclusion, Pearson argued that if we regarded *X*′2 as also distributed as χ2 distribution with *k* − 1 degrees of freedom, the error in this approximation would not affect practical decisions.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] This conclusion caused some controversy in practical applications and was not settled for 20 years until Fisher's 1922 and 1924 papers.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] One test statistic that follows a chi-squared distribution exactly is the test that the variance of a normally distributed population has a given value based on a sample variance.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Such tests are uncommon in practice because the true variance of the population is usually unknown.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] For an exact test used in place of the 2 × 2 chi-squared test for independence when all the row and column totals were fixed by design, see Fisher's exact test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] When the row or column margins (or both) are random variables (as in most common research designs) this tends to be overly conservative and underpowered.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] For an exact test used in place of the 2 × 1 chi-squared test for goodness of fit, see binomial test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Using the chi-squared distribution to interpret Pearson's chi-squared statistic requires one to assume that the discrete probability of observed binomial frequencies in the table can be approximated by the continuous chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] This assumption is not quite correct and introduces some error.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] To reduce the error in approximation, Frank Yates suggested a correction for continuity that adjusts the formula for Pearson's chi-squared test by subtracting 0.5 from the absolute difference between each observed value and its expected value in a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] This reduces the chi-squared value obtained and thus increases its *p*-value.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] If a sample of size *n* is taken from a population having a normal distribution, then there is a result (see distribution of the sample variance) which allows a test to be made of whether the variance of the population has a pre-determined value.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] For example, a manufacturing process might have been in stable condition for a long period, allowing a value for the variance to be determined essentially without error.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Suppose that a variant of the process is being tested, giving rise to a small sample of *n* product items whose variation is to be tested.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The test statistic *T* in this instance could be set to be the sum of squares about the sample mean, divided by the nominal value for the variance (i.e. the value to be tested as holding).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Then *T* has a chi-squared distribution with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] For example, if the sample size is 21, the acceptance region for *T* with a significance level of 5% is between 9.59 and 34.17.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Suppose there is a city of 1,000,000 residents with four neighborhoods: *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] A random sample of 650 residents of the city is taken and their occupation is recorded as "white collar", "blue collar", or "no collar".
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The null hypothesis is that each person's neighborhood of residence is independent of the person's occupational classification.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Let us take the sample living in neighborhood *A*, 150, to estimate what proportion of the whole 1,000,000 live in neighborhood *A*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Similarly we take ⁠349/650⁠ to estimate what proportion of the 1,000,000 are white-collar workers.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The sum of these quantities over all of the cells is the test statistic; in this case, $\approx 24.57$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] If the test statistic is improbably large according to that chi-squared distribution, then one rejects the null hypothesis of independence.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] A related issue is a test of homogeneity.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Suppose that instead of giving every resident of each of the four neighborhoods an equal chance of inclusion in the sample, we decide in advance how many residents of each neighborhood to include.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Then each resident has the same chance of being chosen as do all residents of the same neighborhood, but residents of different neighborhoods would have different probabilities of being chosen if the four sample sizes are not proportional to the populations of the four neighborhoods.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In such a case, we would be testing "homogeneity" rather than "independence".
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The question is whether the proportions of blue-collar, white-collar, and no-collar workers in the four neighborhoods are the same.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] However, the test is done in the same way.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In cryptanalysis, the chi-squared test is used to compare the distribution of plaintext and (possibly) decrypted ciphertext.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The lowest value of the test means that the decryption was successful with high probability.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] This method can be generalized for solving modern cryptographic problems.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In bioinformatics, the chi-squared test is used to compare the distribution of certain properties of genes (e.g., genomic content, mutation rate, interaction network clustering, etc.) belonging to different categories (e.g., disease genes, essential genes, genes on a certain chromosome etc.).
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] The chi-squared test, while widely used for categorical data analysis, has several important limitations that researchers should consider.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] First, it assumes that observations are independent; violating this assumption can lead to misleading results.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Second, the test is sensitive to sample size.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] In very large samples, even trivial differences between observed and expected frequencies may produce statistically significant results, while in very small samples, the test may lack power to detect meaningful associations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Third, the chi-squared test does not measure the strength or practical importance of an association—it only indicates whether a significant relationship exists.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Effect size measures, such as Cramér's V or the contingency coefficient, should be reported alongside the test statistic to provide context.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Finally, the test may be inaccurate when expected frequencies in any cell are very small, often recommended to be at least 5; in such cases, exact tests or alternative methods are preferred.
[src:chi-squared-tests/chi-squared-test] Researchers must also be cautious when dealing with unevenly distributed categories, as dominant groups can overshadow patterns in smaller groups.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] In statistics, a **contingency table** (also known as a **cross tabulation** or **crosstab**) is a type of table in a matrix format that displays the multivariate frequency distribution of the variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] They are heavily used in survey research, business intelligence, engineering, and scientific research.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] They provide a basic picture of the interrelation between two variables and can help find interactions between them.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The term *contingency table* was first used by Karl Pearson in "On the Theory of Contingency and Its Relation to Association and Normal Correlation", part of the *Drapers' Company Research Memoirs Biometric Series I* published in 1904.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] A crucial problem of multivariate statistics is finding the (direct-)dependence structure underlying the variables contained in high-dimensional contingency tables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] If some of the conditional independences are revealed, then even the storage of the data can be done in a smarter way (see Lauritzen (2002)).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] In order to do this one can use information theory concepts, which gain the information only from the distribution of probability, which can be expressed easily from the contingency table by the relative frequencies.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] A pivot table is a way to create contingency tables using spreadsheet software.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Suppose there are two variables, sex (male or female) and handedness (right- or left-handed).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Further suppose that 100 individuals are randomly sampled from a very large population as part of a study of sex differences in handedness.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] A contingency table can be created to display the numbers of individuals who are male right-handed and left-handed, female right-handed and left-handed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Such a contingency table is shown below.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The numbers of the males, females, and right- and left-handed individuals are called marginal totals.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The grand total (the total number of individuals represented in the contingency table) is the number in the bottom right corner.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The table allows users to see at a glance that the proportion of men who are right-handed is about the same as the proportion of women who are right-handed although the proportions are not identical.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The strength of the association can be measured by the odds ratio, and the population odds ratio estimated by the sample odds ratio.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] If the proportions of individuals in the different columns vary significantly between rows (or vice versa), it is said that there is a *contingency* between the two variables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] In other words, the two variables are *not* independent.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] If there is no contingency, it is said that the two variables are *independent*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The example above is the simplest kind of contingency table, a table in which each variable has only two levels; this is called a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] In principle, any number of rows and columns may be used.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] There may also be more than two variables, but higher order contingency tables are difficult to represent visually.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The relation between ordinal variables, or between ordinal and categorical variables, may also be represented in contingency tables, although such a practice is rare.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] For more on the use of a contingency table for the relation between two ordinal variables, see Goodman and Kruskal's gamma.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The degree of association between the two variables can be assessed by a number of coefficients.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The following subsections describe a few of them.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] For a more complete discussion of their uses, see the main articles linked under each subsection heading.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The simplest measure of association for a 2 × 2 contingency table is the odds ratio.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Given two events, A and B, the odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of A in the presence of B and the odds of A in the absence of B, or equivalently (due to symmetry), the ratio of the odds of B in the presence of A and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio is 1; if the odds ratio is greater than 1, the events are positively associated; if the odds ratio is less than 1, the events are negatively associated.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Then its sign equals the sign of the product of the main diagonal elements of the table minus the product of the off–diagonal elements. φ takes on the minimum value −1.0 or the maximum value of +1.0 if and only if every marginal proportion is equal to 0.5 (and two diagonal cells are empty).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Two alternatives are the *contingency coefficient* *C*, and Cramér's V.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Another choice is the tetrachoric correlation coefficient but it is only applicable to 2 × 2 tables.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Polychoric correlation is an extension of the tetrachoric correlation to tables involving variables with more than two levels.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Tetrachoric correlation assumes that the variable underlying each dichotomous measure is normally distributed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The tetrachoric correlation coefficient should not be confused with the Pearson correlation coefficient computed by assigning, say, values 0.0 and 1.0 to represent the two levels of each variable (which is mathematically equivalent to the φ coefficient).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The lambda coefficient is a measure of the strength of association of the cross tabulations when the variables are measured at the nominal level.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Values range from 0.0 (no association) to 1.0 (the maximum possible association).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Asymmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement in predicting the dependent variable.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Symmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement when prediction is done in both directions.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] The uncertainty coefficient, or Theil's U, is another measure for variables at the nominal level.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Its values range from −1.0 (100% negative association, or perfect inversion) to +1.0 (100% positive association, or perfect agreement).
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] A value of 0.0 indicates the absence of association.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] This asymmetrical property can lead to insights not as evident in symmetrical measures of association.
[src:chi-squared-tests/contingency-table] Gamma, Tau-b and Tau-c are used when the categories or levels of both variables have a natural order.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] In statistics, ***G*-tests** are likelihood-ratio or maximum likelihood statistical significance tests that are increasingly being used in situations where chi-squared tests were previously recommended.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] where $O_{i}\geq 0$ is the observed count in a cell, $E_{i}>0$ is the expected count under the null hypothesis, $\ln$ denotes the natural logarithm, and the sum is taken over all non-empty cells.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] The resulting G is asymptotically chi-squared distributed as the total number of observations tends to infinity (convergence in distribution).
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] where N is the total number of observations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Both, the *G*-test statistics G and the chi-square test statistics $\chi ^{2}$ are special cases of a general family of power divergence statistics by Cressie and Read.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] We can derive the value of the *G*-test from the log-likelihood ratio test where the underlying model is a multinomial model.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Suppose we had a sample $O=(O_{1},\ldots ,O_{m})$ where each $O_{i}$ is the number of times that an object of type i was observed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Furthermore, let $N=\sum _{i=1}^{m}O_{i}$ be the total number of observations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] where $E_{i}$ is the expected count of objects of type i under the null hypothesis.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Heuristically, one can imagine $O_{i}$ as continuous and approaching zero, in which case $O_{i}\ln O_{i}\to 0$ , and terms with zero observations can simply be dropped.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] However the *expected* count in each cell must be strictly greater than zero for each cell ( $E_{i}>0$ for all i ) to apply the method.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] For very small samples the multinomial test for goodness of fit, and Fisher's exact test for contingency tables, or even Bayesian hypothesis selection are preferable to the *G*-test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] McDonald recommends to always use an exact test (exact test of goodness-of-fit, Fisher's exact test) if the total sample size is less than 1 000 .
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] shouldn't have any problem doing an exact test on a sample size of 1 000 .
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] The commonly used chi-squared tests for goodness of fit to a distribution and for independence in contingency tables are in fact approximations of the log-likelihood ratio on which the *G*-tests are based.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] The approximation of the *G*-test statistics by chi-squared test statistics is obtained by a second order Taylor expansion of the natural logarithm around 1 (see the derivation below).
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] We have $G\approx \chi ^{2}$ when the observed counts $O_{i}$ are close to the expected counts $E_{i}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] When this difference is large, however, the approximation by the chi-squared test statistics begins to break down.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Here, the effects of outliers in data will be more pronounced, and this explains the why chi-squared tests fail in situations with little data.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] For samples of a reasonable size, the *G*-test and the chi-squared test will lead to the same conclusions.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] However, the approximation to the theoretical chi-squared distribution for the *G*-test is better than for the Pearson's chi-squared test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] In cases where $O_{i}>2\cdot E_{i}$ for some cell case the *G*-test is always better than the chi-squared test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] For testing goodness-of-fit the *G*-test is infinitely more efficient than the chi-squared test in the sense of Bahadur, but the two tests are equally efficient in the sense of Pitman or in the sense of Hodges and Lehmann.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] and let $O_{i}=E_{i}+\delta _{i}$ with $\textstyle \sum _{i}\delta _{i}=0$ , so that the total number of counts remains the same.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Assume that $\delta _{i}=O_{i}-E_{i}$ is small in comparison to $E_{i}$ for all i .
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] To be more precise, notice that $E_{i}=\Theta (n)$ using big *Θ* notation.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] where N is the total number of observations and ${\tilde {p}}_{i}={\tfrac {E_{i}}{N}}$ and ${\hat {p}}_{i}={\tfrac {O_{i}}{N}}$ are the theoretical and empirical probabilities of objects of type i , respectively.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] For analysis of contingency tables the value of the *G*-test statistics can also be expressed in terms of mutual information.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] In this case objects with two-dimensional types $(i,j)$ are considered.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Let $O_{ij}$ be the count of objects of type $(i,j)$ , i.e., $O_{ij}$ is the entry in the contingency table in row i and column j .
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] It can also be shown that the inverse document frequency weighting commonly used for text retrieval is an approximation of *G* applicable when the row sum for the query is much smaller than the row sum for the remainder of the corpus.
[src:chi-squared-tests/g-test] Similarly, the result of Bayesian inference applied to a choice of single multinomial distribution for all rows of the contingency table taken together versus the more general alternative of a separate multinomial per row produces results very similar to the *G*-test statistic.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] The **goodness of fit** of a statistical model describes how well it fits a set of observations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] Measures of goodness of fit typically summarize the discrepancy between observed values and the values expected under the model in question.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] Such measures can be used in statistical hypothesis testing, e.g. to test for normality of residuals, to test whether two samples are drawn from identical distributions (see Kolmogorov–Smirnov test), or whether outcome frequencies follow a specified distribution (see Pearson's chi-square test).
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] In the analysis of variance, one of the components into which the variance is partitioned may be a lack-of-fit sum of squares.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] The following are examples that arise in the context of categorical data.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] The resulting value can be compared with a chi-square distribution to determine the goodness of fit.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] The chi-square distribution has (*k* − *c*) degrees of freedom, where *k* is the number of non-empty bins and *c* is the number of estimated parameters (including location and scale parameters and shape parameters) for the distribution plus one.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] For example, for a 3-parameter Weibull distribution, *c* = 4.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] A binomial experiment is a sequence of independent trials in which the trials can result in one of two outcomes, success or failure.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] There are *n* trials each with probability of success, denoted by *p*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] This has approximately a chi-square distribution with *k* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] The fact that there are *k* − 1 degrees of freedom is a consequence of the restriction ${\textstyle \sum N_{i}=n}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] We know there are *k* observed bin counts, however, once any *k* − 1 are known, the remaining one is uniquely determined.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] Basically, one can say, there are only *k* − 1 freely determined bin counts, thus *k* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] where ${\textstyle O_{i}}$ and ${\textstyle E_{i}}$ are the same as for the chi-square test, ${\textstyle \ln }$ denotes the natural logarithm, and the sum is taken over all non-empty bins.
[src:chi-squared-tests/goodness-of-fit] Furthermore, the total observed count should be equal to the total expected count: $\sum _{i}O_{i}=\sum _{i}E_{i}=N$ where ${\textstyle N}$ is the total number of observations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The commonly used parameters to assess a diagnostic test in medical sciences are sensitivity and specificity.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Sensitivity (or recall) is the ability of a test to correctly identify the people with disease.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Specificity is the ability of the test to correctly identify those without the disease.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Now presume two tests are performed on the same group of patients.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] And also presume that these tests have identical sensitivity and specificity.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] In this situation one is carried away by these findings and presume that both the tests are equivalent.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] For this we have to study the patients with disease and patients without disease (by a reference test).
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] We also have to find out where these two tests disagree with each other.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] This is precisely the basis of McNemar's test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] This test compares the sensitivity and specificity of two diagnostic tests on the same group of patients.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The test is applied to a 2 × 2 contingency table, which tabulates the outcomes of two tests on a sample of *N* subjects, as follows.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The null hypothesis of marginal homogeneity states that the two marginal probabilities for each outcome are the same, i.e.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Here *p**a*, etc., denote the theoretical probability of occurrences in cells with the corresponding label.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Under the null hypothesis, with a sufficiently large number of discordants (cells b and c), $\chi ^{2}$ has a chi-squared distribution with 1 degree of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] If the $\chi ^{2}$ result is significant, this provides sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis, in favour of the alternative hypothesis that *pb* ≠ *pc*, which would mean that the marginal proportions are significantly different from each other.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] If either *b* or *c* is small (*b* + *c* < 25) then $\chi ^{2}$ is not well-approximated by the chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] An exact binomial test can then be used, where *b* is compared to a binomial distribution with size parameter *n* = *b* + *c* and *p* = 0.5.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Effectively, the exact binomial test evaluates the imbalance in the discordants *b* and *c*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] To achieve a two-sided P-value, the P-value of the extreme tail should be multiplied by 2.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] which is simply twice the binomial distribution cumulative distribution function with *p* = 0.5 and *n* = *b* + *c*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] where the second term is the binomial distribution probability mass function and *n* = *b* + *c*.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Binomial distribution functions are readily available in common software packages and the McNemar mid-P test can easily be calculated.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The traditional advice has been to use the exact binomial test when *b* + *c* < 25.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] However, simulations have shown both the exact binomial test and the McNemar test with continuity correction to be overly conservative.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] When *b* + *c* < 6, the exact-P-value always exceeds the common significance level 0.05.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The original McNemar test was most powerful, but often slightly liberal.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The mid-P version was almost as powerful as the asymptotic McNemar test and was not found to exceed the nominal significance level.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] In the first example, a researcher attempts to determine if a drug has an effect on a particular disease.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] There are 314 patients, and they are diagnosed (disease: *present* or *absent*) before and after using the drug, which means that each sample can be described using 1 out of 4 combinations.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Counts of individuals are given in the table, with the diagnosis (disease: *present* or *absent*) before treatment given in the rows, and the diagnosis after treatment in the columns.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The test requires the same subjects to be included in the before-and-after measurements (matched pairs).
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] In this example, the null hypothesis of "marginal homogeneity" would mean there was no effect of the treatment.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] has the value 21.35, which is extremely unlikely to form the distribution implied by the null hypothesis (*p* < 0.001).
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Thus the test provides strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis of no treatment effect.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] A second example illustrates differences between the asymptotic McNemar test and alternatives.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] With these data, the sample size (161 patients) is not small, however results from the McNemar test and other versions are different.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The exact binomial test gives *p* = 0.053 and McNemar's test with continuity correction gives $\chi ^{2}$ = 3.68 and *p* = 0.055.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The asymptotic McNemar's test gives $\chi ^{2}$ = 4.55 and *p* = 0.033 and the mid-P McNemar's test gives *p* = 0.035.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Both the McNemar's test and mid-P version provide stronger evidence for a statistically significant treatment effect in this second example.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The following is an example implementation using the probability distributions provided by the SciPy package.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The implementation uses the mid-P version if *b* + *c* < 25.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Otherwise, it uses the asymptotic version, allowing for both the regular form and the continuity corrected form.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] It is also worth noting that the above implementation ensures that the smaller of *b* and *c* is passed as the first argument to the binomial probability distributions.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] See "Additional file 1" under the supplementary materials for further reading.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] An interesting observation when interpreting McNemar's test is that the elements of the main diagonal do not contribute to the decision about whether (in the above example) pre- or post-treatment condition is more favourable.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Thus, the sum *b* + *c* can be small and statistical power of the tests described above can be low even though the number of pairs *a* + *b* + *c* + *d* is large (see second example above).
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] An extension of McNemar's test exists in situations where independence does not necessarily hold between the pairs; instead, there are clusters of paired data where the pairs in a cluster may not be independent, but independence holds between different clusters.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] In the 1970s, it was conjectured that retaining one's tonsils might protect against Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] It is to the second table that McNemar's test can be applied.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] Notice that the sum of the numbers in the second table is 85—the number of *pairs* of siblings—whereas the sum of the numbers in the first table is twice as big, 170—the number of individuals.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The second table gives more information than the first.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The numbers in the first table can be found by using the numbers in the second table, but not vice versa.
[src:chi-squared-tests/mcnemar-s-test] The numbers in the first table give only the marginal totals of the numbers in the second table.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] A simple example is testing the hypothesis that an ordinary six-sided die is "fair" (i. e., all six outcomes are equally likely to occur).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] In this case, the observed data is $(O_{1},O_{2},...,O_{6})$ , the number of times that the die has fallen on each number.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] As detailed below, if $\chi ^{2}>11.07$ , then the fairness of the die can be rejected at the level of $p<0.05$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Pearson's chi-squared test is used to assess three types of comparison: goodness of fit, homogeneity, and independence.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Determine the degrees of freedom, **df**, of that statistic.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] For a test of homogeneity, df = (Rows − 1)×(Cols − 1), where *Rows* corresponds to the number of categories (i.e. rows in the associated contingency table), and *Cols* corresponds to the number of independent groups (i.e. columns in the associated contingency table).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] For a test of independence, df = (Rows − 1)×(Cols − 1), where in this case, *Rows* corresponds to the number of categories in one variable, and *Cols* corresponds to the number of categories in the second variable.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Select a desired level of confidence (significance level, *p*-value, or the corresponding alpha level) for the result of the test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Sustain or reject the null hypothesis that the observed frequency distribution is the same as the theoretical distribution based on whether the test statistic exceeds the critical value of $\chi ^{2}$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] If the test statistic falls below the threshold $\chi ^{2}$ value, then no clear conclusion can be reached, and the null hypothesis is sustained (we fail to reject the null hypothesis), though not necessarily accepted.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] In this case N observations are divided among n cells.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] A simple application is to test the hypothesis that, in the general population, values would occur in each cell with equal frequency.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The "theoretical frequency" for any cell (under the null hypothesis of a discrete uniform distribution) is thus calculated as $E_{i}={\frac {N}{n}}\,,$ and the reduction in the degrees of freedom is $p=1$ , notionally because the observed frequencies $O_{i}$ are constrained to sum to N .
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] One specific example of its application would be its application for log-rank test.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] When testing whether observations are random variables whose distribution belongs to a given family of distributions, the "theoretical frequencies" are calculated using a distribution from that family fitted in some standard way.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The reduction in the degrees of freedom is calculated as $p=s+1$ , where s is the number of parameters used in fitting the distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] For instance, when checking a three-parameter Generalized gamma distribution, $p=4$ , and when checking a normal distribution (where the parameters are mean and standard deviation), $p=3$ , and when checking a Poisson distribution (where the parameter is the expected value), $p=2$ .
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Thus, there will be $n-p$ degrees of freedom, where n is the number of categories.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The degrees of freedom are not based on the number of observations as with a Student's t or F-distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] For example, if testing for a fair, six-sided die, there would be five degrees of freedom because there are six categories or parameters (each number); the number of times the die is rolled does not influence the number of degrees of freedom.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The chi-squared statistic can then be used to calculate a p-value by comparing the value of the statistic to a chi-squared distribution.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The number of degrees of freedom is equal to the number of cells n , minus the reduction in degrees of freedom, p .
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] This result is the consequence of the Binomial theorem.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The result about the numbers of degrees of freedom is valid when the original data are multinomial and hence the estimated parameters are efficient for minimizing the chi-squared statistic.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] More generally however, when maximum likelihood estimation does not coincide with minimum chi-squared estimation, the distribution will lie somewhere between a chi-squared distribution with $n-1-p$ and $n-1$ degrees of freedom (See for instance Chernoff and Lehmann, 1954).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The chi-squared test indicates a statistically significant association between the level of education completed and routine check-up attendance (chi2(3) = 14.6090, p = 0.002).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The proportions suggest that as the level of education increases, so does the proportion of individuals attending routine check-ups.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Specifically, individuals who have graduated from college or university attend routine check-ups at a higher proportion (31.52%) compared to those who have not graduated high school (8.44%).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] This finding may suggest that higher educational attainment is associated with a greater likelihood of engaging in health-promoting behaviors such as routine check-ups.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] In Bayesian statistics, one would instead use a Dirichlet distribution as conjugate prior.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] If one took a uniform prior, then the maximum likelihood estimate for the population probability is the observed probability, and one may compute a credible region around this or another estimate.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] In this case, an "observation" consists of the values of two outcomes and the null hypothesis is that the occurrence of these outcomes is statistically independent.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Each observation is allocated to one cell of a two-dimensional array of cells (called a contingency table) according to the values of the two outcomes.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] is the fraction of observations of type *j* ignoring the row attribute (fraction of column totals).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The term "frequencies" refers to absolute numbers rather than already normalized values.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Note that $\chi ^{2}$ is 0 if and only if $O_{i,j}=E_{i,j}\forall i,j$ , i.e. only if the expected and true number of observations are equal in all cells.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Fitting the model of "independence" reduces the number of degrees of freedom by *p* = *r* + *c* − 1.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The number of degrees of freedom is equal to the number of cells *rc*, minus the reduction in degrees of freedom, *p*, which reduces to (*r* − 1)(*c* − 1).
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The alternative hypothesis corresponds to the variables having an association or relationship where the structure of this relationship is not specified.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] The sample data is a random sampling from a fixed distribution or population where every collection of members of the population of the given sample size has an equal probability of selection.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Variants of the test have been developed for complex samples, such as where the data is weighted.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] A sample with a sufficiently large size is assumed.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] If a chi squared test is conducted on a sample with a smaller size, then the chi squared test will yield an inaccurate inference.
[src:chi-squared-tests/pearson-s-chi-squared-test] Some require 5 or more, and others require 10 or more.
